<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is capacitance?", answer: "Capacitance is the ability of a component to store electrical charge, measured in farads (F). It is defined as C = Q/V, where Q is the charge stored in coulombs and V is the voltage across the capacitor. One farad is the capacitance that stores one coulomb when one volt is applied. In practice, most capacitors are measured in microfarads (uF), nanofarads (nF), or picofarads (pF) because one farad is an extremely large capacitance." },
  { question: "How do capacitors in series and parallel differ?", answer: "In series, the total capacitance decreases: 1/Ct = 1/C1 + 1/C2 + ... The voltage divides across capacitors but the charge on each is the same. In parallel, capacitances add directly: Ct = C1 + C2 + ... The voltage across each is the same but the total charge is the sum. Series is the opposite behavior of resistors: resistors in series add, but capacitors in series give a smaller total. This is because series capacitors share charge while parallel capacitors share voltage." },
  { question: "How much energy does a capacitor store?", answer: "The energy stored in a capacitor is E = 1/2 * C * V^2, where C is capacitance and V is voltage. This can also be written as E = Q^2/(2C) or E = QV/2. The energy comes from the work done to move charge against the electric field. A 1000uF capacitor charged to 50V stores 1.25 joules. Supercapacitors can store much more energy and are used in regenerative braking systems and backup power supplies." },
  { question: "What are common capacitor applications?", answer: "Capacitors are used for energy storage (camera flashes, UPS systems), filtering (smoothing DC power supplies, removing noise), timing (RC circuits in oscillators and timers), coupling and decoupling (passing AC signals while blocking DC), power factor correction (in industrial AC systems), and tuning (radio frequency selection). Every electronic device from smartphones to power grids relies on capacitors." },
  { question: "What is the difference between a capacitor and a battery?", answer: "Both store energy, but in different ways. Capacitors store energy in an electric field between plates and can charge/discharge almost instantly, but store relatively little energy. Batteries store energy chemically and can hold much more energy but charge/discharge slowly. Capacitors last millions of charge cycles while batteries degrade. Supercapacitors bridge the gap with higher energy density than regular capacitors but faster response than batteries." }
]) %>

